{"title_page": "John Richards (Attorney General)", "text_new": "'''John Richards'''  [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]] (1790 \u2013 1872) was an Irish  lawyer and judge.\n\n==Early life==\nRichards was born in 1790<ref name=\"Burke\">{{cite book|author=Burke, Bernard.|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H65CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1164|edition=5th|volume=II|year=1871|publisher=Harrison|location=London|pages=1164}}</ref> in [[Dublin]], the younger son of John Nunn Richards, [[solicitor]], and his  first wife Elizabeth Fitzgerald.  His father's family  originally came from [[Rathaspick, County Wexford]], and his father had a  country house at Hermitage nearby.  He graduated from the [[University of Dublin]].\n\n==Career==\nHe was [[called to the Bar]] in 1811,  and became [[King's Counsel]] in 1830.\n\nHe was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Daniel O'Connell]], and  in later years  recalled with gratitude  O'Connell. coming to his assistance in a case where the judges would not hear him: O'Connell argued the case on his behalf with frequent references  to what \"Mr. Richards would have said if he had been permitted to\";<ref>Geoghegan, Patrick M.  ''King Dan- the rise of Daniel O'Connell''  Gilll and Macmillan Dublin 2008 p.62-3</ref>  Richards   never ceased to praise O'Connell's \"ability and perseverance\".<ref>Geoghegan pp.62-3</ref> Like O'Connell, he was a staunch supporter of [[Catholic Emancipation]].\n\nHe was appointed a judge at [[Madras]] in 1835 but resigned that office in order  to become [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]  in the same year,  and he  became [[Attorney-General for Ireland]] the following year. He was appointed a Baron of the  [[Court of Exchequer (Ireland)]] in 1837 and held that office until 1859; he also served as a judge of the Encumbered Estates Court.\n\n==Family and personal life==\n\nRichards married firstly  in 1815 Catherine Moloney, daughter of Henry Gonne Moloney,  barrister, of [[Tulla]], [[County Clare]], and his wife Caroline Walker,  by whom he had seven children, three sons and four daughters:<ref>Burke  ''Landed Gentry of Great Britain and Ireland'' London 1846 Vol. 2</ref> John, William, Oswald, Elizabeth who married a Mr. Rolleston, Catherine who married Thomas Spunner, Charlotte who married a Mr. Symes,  and  Henrietta-Caroline, who married Robert King Piers, nephew of Sir Robert King, 2nd Baronet of the [[King Baronets|King Baronets, of Charlestown ]]  in 1844.<ref>''The Gentleman's Magazine'' 1844</ref>\n\nHe married  secondly  in 1832 Christiana O'Brien, daughter of Christopher James O'Brien, but had no further issue.\n\nHis eldest don John became a [[County Court]]  judge. One of his sons, Henry, in turn became Chief Justice of the [[Allahabad High Court]],  [[India]].\n\nHe was elected a member of the [[Royal Dublin Society]] in 1831. In Dublin he lived in [[Dalkey]], and later [[Dundrum, Dublin|Dundrum]], and he also had a country house in [[County Clare]].\n\nBall describes him as one of the finest Irish judges of his time.<ref>Ball, F. Elrington ''The Judges in Ireland 1221-1921 John Murray London 1926</ref>\n''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir Michael O'Loghlen, 1st Baronet|Michael O'Loghlen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]|years=1835&ndash;1836 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Woulfe]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir Michael O'Loghlen, 1st Baronet|Michael O'Loghlen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney-General for Ireland]]|years=1836&ndash;1837 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Woulfe]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richards, John}}\n[[Category:1790 births]]\n[[Category:1872 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Solicitors-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Barons of the Irish Exchequer]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Richards'''  [[Privy Council of Ireland|PC]] (1790 \u2013 1872) was an Irish  lawyer and judge.\n\n==Early life==\nRichards was born in 1790<ref name=\"Burke\">{{cite book|author=Burke, Bernard.|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry of Great Britain & Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H65CAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1164|edition=5th|volume=II|year=1871|publisher=Harrison|location=London|pages=1164}}</ref> in [[Dublin]], the younger son of John Nunn Richards, [[solicitor]], and his  first wife Elizabeth Fitzgerald.  His father's family  originally came from [[Rathaspick, County Wexford]], and his father had a  country house at Hermitage nearby.  He graduated from the [[University of Dublin]].\n\n==Career==\nHe was [[called to the Bar]] in 1811,  and became [[King's Counsel]] in 1830.\n\nHe was a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Daniel O'Connell]], and  in later years  recalled with gratitude  O'Connell. coming to his assistance in a case where the judges would not hear him: O'Connell argued the case on his behalf with frequent references  to what \"Mr. Richards would have said if he had been permitted to\";<ref>Geoghegan, Patrick M.  ''King Dan- the rise of Daniel O'Connell''  Gilll and Macmillan Dublin 2008 p.62-3</ref>  Richards   never ceased to praise O'Connell's \"ability and perseverance\".<ref>Geoghegan pp.62-3</ref> Like O'Connell, he was a staunch supporter of [[Catholic Emancipation]].\n\nHe was appointed a judge at [[Madras]] in 1835 but resigned that office in order  to become [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]  in the same year,  and he  became [[Attorney-General for Ireland]] the following year. He was appointed a Baron of the  [[Court of Exchequer (Ireland)]] in 1837 and held that office until 1859; he also served as a judge of the Encumbered Estates Court.\n\n==Family and personal life==\n\nRichards married firstly  in 1815 Catherine Moloney, daughter of Henry Gonne Moloney,  barrister, of [[Tulla]], [[County Clare]], and his wife Caroline Walker,  by whom he had seven children, three sons and four daughters:<ref>Burke  ''Landed Gentry of Great Britain and Ireland'' London 1846 Vol. 2</ref> John, William, Oswald, Elizabeth who married a Mr. Rolleston, Catherine who married Thomas Spunner, Charlotte who married a Mr. Symes,  and  Henrietta-Caroline, who married Robert King Piers, nephew of Sir Robert King, 2nd Baronet of the [[King Baronets|King Baronets, of Charlestown ]]  in 1844.<ref>''The Gentleman's Magazine'' 1844</ref>\n\nHe married  secondly  in 1832 Christiana O'Brien, daughter of Christopher James O'Brien.\n\nHis eldest don John became a [[County Court]]  judge. One of his sons, Henry, in turn became Chief Justice of the [[Allahabad High Court]],  [[India]].\n\nHe was elected a member of the [[Royal Dublin Society]] in 1831. In Dublin he lived in [[Dalkey]], and later [[Dundrum, Dublin|Dundrum]], and he also had a country house in [[County Clare]].\n\nBall describes him as one of the finest Irish judges of his time.<ref>Ball, F. Elrington ''The Judges in Ireland 1221-1921 John Murray London 1926</ref>\n''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir Michael O'Loghlen, 1st Baronet|Michael O'Loghlen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Solicitor-General for Ireland]]|years=1835&ndash;1836 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Woulfe]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir Michael O'Loghlen, 1st Baronet|Michael O'Loghlen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney-General for Ireland]]|years=1836&ndash;1837 }}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Woulfe]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richards, John}}\n[[Category:1790 births]]\n[[Category:1872 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Solicitors-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General for Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Barons of the Irish Exchequer]]\n", "name_user": "Chrisdoyleorwell", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily and personal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.or